column12: METHOD OF MAKING ELECTROPHOTOGRAPHIC DEVELOPER FOR ETCH RESIST IMAGE PATTERNS

column15: GARRETT WALTER L;;GILLESPIE HENDERSON C;;SCIAMBI LOUIS J

column13: 1,212,025. Liquid electro-photographic developers. DOW CHEMICAL CO. Nov.3, 1967 [Nov.7, 1966 (2)], No.50145/67. Heading G2H. [Also in Division C3] A liquid electro-photographic developer comprises an anhydrous, inert, organic carrier liquid having dispersed therein a cross-linkable resin which contains hydroxyl groups and a catalyst for curing said resin on heating in the absence of solvent wherein the developer has an electrical conductivity at ambient temperatures of 0À5 x 10<SP>-11</SP> to 1À0 x 10<SP>-9</SP> reciprocal ohm centimetres specified resins are silicone and epoxy resins e.g. a phenyl alkyl siloxane resin. Specified catalysts are alkoxy and dialkoxy aluminium salts of fatty acids e.g. octanoic acid and compounds of the formula:- wherein R<SP>1</SP> is a fatty acid radical of 6-12c, n is 2 or 3, m is 1, 2 or 3 and R is alkyl of 1-4C. Specified carrier liquids are isoparaffinic hydrocarbons, chlorofluorocarbons, aliphatic naphthas, odorless mineral spirits and aromatic hydrocarbons. The developer may contain pigments e.g. black and red iron oxide, ultramarine blue, lead phthalocyanine, or copper phthalocyanine and surfactants e.g. halogenated diaryl oxide sulphonates; sodium ligno sulphonates alkyl naphthalene sulphonates and alkali metal salts of sulphonated oils.

column12: Spinal deformity correction instruments and methods
column13: An instrument for correction of spinal deformities includes an inner member with a proximal portion configured to receive a corrective force and a distal coupling portion configured to transfer the corrective force to a spinal implant in a vertebra. A slot extends transversely through the coupling portion and is configured to guide a fixation rod into the spinal implant. A threaded sleeve includes an external thread and a thru-bore that slides relative to the proximal portion. An outer member couples with the proximal portion and threadably engages the external thread to apply a reduction force as the outer member rotates relative to the inner member. A reduction blade includes a proximal interlocking portion that removably couples with the threaded sleeve and a distal rod engagement feature configured to engage the fixation rod and transfer the reduction force to reduce the fixation rod into the spinal implant.
